{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the flow of electric current in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Think of it like a flow meter on a water pipe measuring how much water passes through.",
      "misconception": "Thinking an ammeter measures voltage just because it is part of a multimeter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference (voltage) between two points.",
      "anchor": "Like a pressure gauge measuring the difference in pressure between two parts of a system.",
      "misconception": "Confusing it with an ammeter and trying to measure current with it."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure electrical resistance.",
      "anchor": "Measuring how much a pipe is 'clogged' or resisting the flow of water.",
      "misconception": "Believing you can use an ohmmeter on a live circuit; the circuit must be isolated (dead)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure electrical power, which is the rate at which energy is used.",
      "anchor": "Like a speedometer showing how fast you are using energy at this exact moment.",
      "misconception": "Confusing instantaneous power (Watts) with total energy used over time (kWh)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument (often called a kWh meter) that measures the total electrical energy consumed over time.",
      "anchor": "The meter outside a house that the electricity company uses to calculate the bill.",
      "misconception": "Thinking an energy meter and a wattmeter do the same thing; one is for a moment in time, the other is a total over time."
    },
    {
      "term": "Multimeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A versatile tool that combines several measurement functions, such as voltage, current, and resistance, into one unit.",
      "anchor": "The 'Swiss Army Knife' of electrical testing tools.",
      "misconception": "Assuming a multimeter is always set to the right mode automatically; you must select the correct function for the quantity you are measuring."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Ammeters measure current.",
    "Voltmeters measure voltage.",
    "Ohmmeters measure resistance.",
    "Wattmeters measure power.",
    "Energy meters measure energy consumption.",
    "A multimeter combines several functions into one device."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using an ohmmeter on a live circuit.",
    "Confusing a wattmeter with an energy meter.",
    "Selecting the wrong function on a multimeter for the quantity being measured.",
    "Thinking current and voltage are measured by the same instrument setting."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Measuring Current, Voltage, and Resistance",
      "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure current (Ammeter), voltage (Voltmeter), and resistance (Ohmmeter).",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To maintain and troubleshoot electrical systems, you must use the correct tool for the specific quantity you are measuring. We start with the three most common measurements: current, voltage, and resistance.",
        "To measure the flow of electricity, known as current, you use an Ammeter. If you need to check the electrical pressure or potential difference between two points, you use a Voltmeter. When checking how much a component opposes the flow of current, you use an Ohmmeter to measure resistance.",
        "It is vital to remember that an Ohmmeter must only be used on isolated, 'dead' circuits; using it on a live circuit will likely damage the meter. In the field, you will often use a Multimeter. This is a versatile 'Swiss Army Knife' tool that combines an ammeter, voltmeter, and ohmmeter into one unit. However, you must always ensure the dial is set to the correct function before connecting it to a circuit, as measuring voltage while on a current setting can cause a dangerous short circuit."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the names of the units: Amps are measured by an Ammeter, Volts by a Voltmeter, and Ohms by an Ohmmeter."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
      "objective": "Identify the instruments used to measure electrical power (Wattmeter) and electrical energy (Energy meter/kWh meter).",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Beyond basic current and voltage, electricians often need to measure how much work a system is doing. This involves measuring power and energy, which are related but distinct quantities.",
        "Electrical power is the rate at which energy is being used at any given moment. To measure this instantaneous rate, you use a Wattmeter. Think of a Wattmeter like a speedometer in a car; it tells you how fast energy is being consumed right now. If a heater is turned on, the Wattmeter shows the immediate load it puts on the system.",
        "On the other hand, if you need to know the total amount of electricity used over a period of time—such as a day or a month—you use an Energy Meter, also known as a kWh meter. This is the device found at the service head of a building that the electricity company uses for billing. While a Wattmeter shows the immediate power demand, the Energy Meter records the cumulative consumption over time. Selecting the correct meter is essential for accurate load assessment and billing."
      ],
      "hint": "One meter shows the 'speed' of energy use (Watts), while the other acts like an 'odometer' recording the total distance traveled (kWh)."
    }
  ]
}

